# Dirac product style & UX (Cursor for communications)

## Product personality
- Calm, high-signal, no fluff.
- Always make it clear: **what’s selected**, **what will happen**, **what to do next**.

## Layout principles
- Default to **three-pane**: list (left) / content (center) / AI (right, toggleable).
- AI is a **tool**, not the destination; it must not block reading/sending.
- Scope should be visible (e.g., “Context: 3 threads” with a quick details affordance).

## Density & progressive disclosure
- Compact, scannable UI by default.
- Show short summaries first; allow expand for detail.
- Keep “Assumptions” optional/collapsible.

## Action-first interactions
- Each screen must answer “what can I do here?” with obvious actions:
  - Inbox: filters, multi-select actions
  - Thread: reply/send, mark done/snooze/tag
  - AI sidebar: quick actions row; MCQ card only when needed
- Avoid requiring typing for common operations.

## Multi-platform clarity (without fragmentation)
- Unified default view; indicate platform differences (icon, message type, action availability).
- Avoid per-platform tabs; use filters and saved views instead.

## Drafting UX safety
- Autosave drafts locally, allow easy revert/discard.
- “Send” is always explicit; never implicit sending.

## Keyboard-first (design for it now)
- Plan for: j/k navigate, enter open, cmd+enter send, tab/shift-tab focus.

## Visual style
- Neutral surfaces, subtle borders, minimal shadows.
- One accent color for primary actions.
- Avoid heavy gradients/illustrations; content is the product.
- Follow the visual design system in `dirac-visual-design-system.mdc` (inspirations, colorways, tokens, guardrails).
